[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.   

Sometimes using Negative Doubles seems like you can read minds. You know for sure that partner has 4 \Ss since that is the only unbid Major. You know for sure that partner has 10+ points because he made a Negative Double of a 2-level overcall. So you conclude that your side has 8 \Ss and 27+ points . . .. . . and you bid 4\S.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:86.Q975.KQT.AQJ5 QJ.K43.AJ875.K72 KT94.AJ8.932.T96 A7532.T62.64.843"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "1NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1C 1D 1S pass 1NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "5a93fc95f704fe77135c282514c5e7a7131733e129b0fb8496dac6d45a9df806"]
[Category "Competitive Bidding"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "competitive_bidding/negative_doubles"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.   

The general guideline for a Negative Double when both Majors are unbid is that you must have 4+ cards in at least <b>ONE</b> of the Majors. But for this specific sequence, 1\C - 1\D, you do not double unless you have <b>BOTH</b> Majors. When you have only one of them you just bid it. Like this hand. You bid 1\S. Partner rebids 1NT.  

Partner has a minimum hand and fewer than 4 \Ss. A good time for you to pass.}

